# --- Negations: small regenerated artifacts that ARE committed -----------------
# These survive GitHub Actions cache eviction so CI certifies autonomously
# WITHOUT any local machine in the loop (Edge-Factory parity). They are small
# JSON/markdown registries + reports, never the huge raw history CSVs.
!localdata/edges_registry.json
!localdata/edges_consensus.json
!localdata/tipster_audit.json
!localdata/tipster_audit.md
!localdata/entity_registry.json
!localdata/completed_games_audit.json
# Certification chain consumed by certify_roi.py / picks_today.py gating:
!localdata/source_accuracy.json
!localdata/certification_report.json
!localdata/calibration_params.json
!localdata/reliability_diagram.json
!localdata/tipster_prob_calibration.json
!localdata/walk_forward_results.json

# NOTE on the BIG history data (results_kaggle.csv, odds_kaggle.csv, the
# per-source tipster archive *.csv.gz, warehouse.duckdb): these stay IGNORED.
# They are too large to live in normal commits. Provision them once on the CI
# runner exactly like Edge-Factory committed its 3 core history CSVs — e.g.
# commit them with Git LFS, restore from a release asset, or hydrate from
# Supabase/object storage in an extra workflow step. The pipeline degrades
# gracefully (WATCHLIST_* instead of CERTIFIED) when they are absent.

# Stray data files accidentally created in repo root (no extension)
# Date-named files like "2026-06-14" should not be committed
/[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]-[0-9][0-9]-[0-9][0-9]
